# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: auburn-new-york
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:auburn-new-york/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:auburn-new-york/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:auburn-new-york/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:auburn-new-york/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:auburn-new-york/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:auburn-new-york/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:auburn-new-york/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The region around Auburn had been Haudenosaunee territory for centuries before European contact and historical records.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Auburn was founded in 1793, during the post-Revolutionary period of settlement of western New York.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Hardenbergh, was a veteran of the Sullivan-Clinton campaign against the Iroquois during the American Revolution.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Hardenbergh settled in the vicinity of the Owasco River with his infant daughter and two African-American indentured servants, Harry and Kate Freeman.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] After his death in 1806, Hardenbergh was buried in Auburn's North Street Cemetery, and was re-interred in 1852 in Fort Hill Cemetery – the first burial in the city's newly opened burial ground.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The community grew up around Hardenbergh's gristmill and sawmill.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Originally known as Hardenbergh's Corners in the town of Aurelius, the settlement was renamed Auburn in 1805 when it became the county seat.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] It became an incorporated village in 1815, and was chartered as a city in 1848.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] It was only a few miles from the Erie Canal, which opened in 1825 and allowed local factories to inexpensively ship goods north or south.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 1871, the Southern Central Railroad, financed by the Lehigh Valley Railroad, completed a line primarily to carry anthracite coal from Athens, Pennsylvania, through Auburn to wharves on Lake Ontario at Fair Haven.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] From 1818 to 1939, Auburn was home to Auburn Theological Seminary, one of the preeminent theological seminaries in the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 1939, facing financial difficulties as a result of the Great Depression, the seminary moved to the campus of Union Theological Seminary in New York City.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The only building from the Auburn Theological Seminary that stands today is Willard Memorial Chapel and the adjacent Welch Memorial Hall on Nelson Street, designed by Andrew Jackson Warner of Rochester, with stained-glass windows and interior decoration by Louis Comfort Tiffany.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] It is the only complete and unaltered Tiffany chapel interior known to exist.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 1816, Auburn Prison (now the Auburn Correctional Facility) was founded as a model for the contemporary ideas about treating prisoners, known now as the Auburn system.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Visitors were charged a fee for viewing the facility and its inmates.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] On August 6, 1890, the first execution by the electric chair was carried out at Auburn Prison.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 1901 Leon Czolgosz, assassin of President William McKinley, was executed there.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Although the ideas of the Auburn System have been abandoned, the prison continues to serve as a maximum security facility, and is one of the most secure prisons in the continental United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Auburn is located at 42.9317° N, 76.5661° W at the north end of Owasco Lake, one of the Finger Lakes, which is drained by the Owasco Outlet – also known as the Owasco River – which runs north through the city on its way to the Seneca River.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] A dam, owned and operated by the city, controls the outflow of the lake, which is used for drinking water and recreation.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The city is required to keep a sufficient amount of water in the river to deal with the effluent from its waste disposal treatment facility.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city has a total area of 8.4 square miles (21.8 km2), of which 8.3 square miles (21.6 km2) is land and 0.08 square miles (0.2 km2), or 0.89%, is water.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] US 20 is an important east-west highway passing through the city, and New York State Route 34 and New York State Route 38 are north-south highways that intersect US-20 in Auburn.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Seneca Falls is 15 miles (24 km) west on US 20, and Syracuse is 26 miles (42 km) to the northeast via New York State Route 5.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] This climatic region is typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] According to the Köppen Climate Classification system, Auburn has a humid continental climate, abbreviated "Dfb" on climate maps.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] As of the 2020 census, Auburn had a population of 26,866.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] 20.0% of residents were under the age of 18 and 19.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] For every 100 females there were 100.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 98.6 males age 18 and over.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] 99.7% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.3% lived in rural areas.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] There were 11,652 households in Auburn, of which 25.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Of all households, 27.7% were married-couple households, 24.4% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 36.7% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] About 40.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] There were 12,948 housing units, of which 10.0% were vacant.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.8% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.2%.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] As of the census of 2000, there were 28,574 people, 11,411 households, and 6,538 families residing in the city.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The population density was 3,405.3 inhabitants per square mile (1,314.8/km2).
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] There were 12,637 housing units at an average density of 1,506.0 per square mile (581.5/km2).
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The racial makeup of the city was 88.57% White, 7.59% African American, 0.29% Native American, 0.57% Asian, 0.02% Pacific Islander, 1.41% from other races, and 1.55% from two or more races.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 2.82% of the population.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] There were 11,411 households, out of which 28.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 37.3% were married couples living together, 14.7% had a female householder with no partner present, and 42.7% were non-families.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] 36.3% of all households were made up of individuals, and 16.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The average household size was 2.27 and the average family size was 2.98.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In the city, the population was spread out, with 22.8% under the age of 18, 9.3% from 18 to 24, 30.3% from 25 to 44, 19.8% from 45 to 64, and 17.8% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] For every 100 females, there were 99.0 males.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 97.8 males.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The median income for a household in the city was $30,281, and the median income for a family was $41,169.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Males had a median income of $32,349 versus $23,330 for females.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The per capita income for the city was $17,083.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] About 12.5% of families and 16.5% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.9% of those under age 18 and 10.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The Auburn Enlarged City School District is the public school system including almost all of the city of Auburn.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] It currently operates seven schools covering grades K–12.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] West Middle School was closed over the summer of 2011 to save funds, with the student population merged into East Middle School.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] A small piece of Auburn is in the Port Byron Central School District.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The only college in Auburn is Cayuga Community College, a two-year school.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] C.C.C., as it is known locally, is located on Franklin Street.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The city had been the home of Auburn Theological Seminary, a Presbyterian institution established in 1818, which relocated to New York City in 1939.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Auburn has had a long association with professional baseball.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The Auburn Cayugas and other early Auburn teams played as members of the League Alliance (1877), Central New York League (1888), New York State League (1889, 1897–1899), Empire State League (1906–1907), Canadian–American League (1938, 1940) and Border League (1946–1951).
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Auburn was an affiliate of the Boston Red Sox (1948).
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Today, Auburn is home to the Auburn Doubledays, members of the collegiate wooden bat Perfect Game Collegiate Baseball League.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In late 1901, Auburn became the headquarters of the National Association of Professional Baseball Leagues (NAPBL), which is now known simply as Minor League Baseball and based in St.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Farrell, who served as secretary-treasurer of the league for many years, was a local resident, and the league's offices remained in the city while he remained in that role.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Auburn Community Baseball, which is owned by the City of Auburn, is the parent organization of the Auburn Doubledays and its predecessor Auburn entries in the Class A short-season New York–Penn League dating back to 1958.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The team plays its home games at Leo Pinckney Field at Falcon Park.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Until 2020 they were members of the New York-Penn League.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Since 1978, on the second Sunday of every August, Auburn has hosted "The Great Race", a three- or four-person relay race involving running, cycling, and canoeing (or kayaking).
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The race begins and ends in the area of Owasco Lake on the southern outskirts of Auburn.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] With between 2,000 and 2,500 people participating in an average year, it is one of the largest relay races in the United States.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The daily newspaper published in Auburn is *The Citizen*, which dates back to 1816, and had previously been published as *The Daily Advertiser* and *The Citizen-Advertiser*.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] It serves Auburn and Cayuga County, as well as other parts of Central New York.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] A morning paper, published seven days a week, it has a circulation of 10,000 for the daily and Saturday editions, and 12,000 on Sunday.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Possibly the two best-known historical figures associated with Auburn are Harriet Tubman and William H.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Seward's wife, Frances Adeline Seward, was deeply committed to the abolitionist movement, which was strongly supported in Auburn.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In the 1850s, the Seward family opened their Auburn home as a safehouse to fugitive slaves on the Underground Railroad.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 1859 Seward sold a plot of land to abolitionist Tubman, who used it to create a safe haven for her family and friends and other black Americans seeking a better life in the north.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Seward's house is now a historical museum, and both it and Tubman's house are on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Peter's Episcopal Church Complex, Sand Beach Church, Schines Auburn Theatre, Thompson AME Zion Church, Harriet Tubman Grave, Harriet Tubman House, the Old Post Office and Courthouse, Fort Hill Cemetery, Wall Street Methodist Episcopal Church, and Dr.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] Seward House and Willard Memorial Chapel-Welch Memorial Hall are National Historic Landmarks, and the South Street Area Historic District is a national historic district.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] In 2018, the NYS Equal Rights Heritage Center opened to the public, serving as a visitors' center and permanent exhibition promoting the region's history and culture.
[src:auburn-new-york/auburn-new-york] The center guides visitors to the variety of historical sites in the region connected to the struggle for equal rights.
